just_use hints.go

# label: WORKHORSE (hint-enumeration)
# role: domain — enumerate every legal move from (board, hand) state

Exhaustively lists legal merges: hand-card → board stack, and
board stack → board stack. Caller picks which subset to display
or act on.

## Exposed surface

- `type HintKind string` — `"merge_hand" | "merge_stack"`.
- `type Hint struct { Kind, HandCard?, SourceStack?, TargetStack, Side, ResultScore }`.
- `LegalHandMerges(hand, board) []Hint`
- `LegalStackMerges(board) []Hint`
- `AllLegalMerges(hand, board) []Hint` — concat.

`ResultScore` previews board score if the hint is played.
Computed via `scoreAfterReplace` — pure, no state change.

## Consumer endpoint

`GET /gopher/lynrummy-elm/sessions/<id>/hints` returns
`{base_score, hand_merges:[Hint...], stack_merges:[Hint...]}`
after replaying the session's action log.

## Why this belongs here (not in Python)

Python client is intentionally dumb. Rule knowledge lives on
the Go+Elm enumerate-and-bridge spine. A Python player asks
"what's legal?" via this endpoint rather than computing
locally — that way we don't create a third implementation
that could drift.

## Deferred

- Splits aren't reported. A split is always structurally
  legal at any size-≥-2 stack; listing them would drown the
  hints output in no-op suggestions. If an agent wants to
  propose splits, it should enumerate `(stack, cardIdx)` on
  its own.
- Placements (hand → empty board loc) aren't reported — also
  always legal, infinitely many locations. Caller proposes.
- `merge_stack` pairs enumerate every `(source, target)`; in
  a symmetric set merge both `A→B` and `B→A` appear. Caller
  filters if they want unique merges.
